For much heat and moisture would then abound in the fields 3 and therefore wherever a suitable spot offered, wombs would grow attached to the earth by roots 3 and when the warmth of the infants, flying the wet and craving the air, had opened these in the fulness of time, nature would turn to that spot the pores of the earth and constrain it to yield from its opened veins a liquid most like to milk, even as now-a—days every woman when she has borne, is filled with sweet milk, because all that current of nutri- ment streams towards the breasts. To the children the earth would furnish food, the heat raiment, the grass a bed rich in abundance of soft down. But the fresh youth of the world would give forth neither severe colds nor excessivo heats nor gales of great violence 3 for all things grow and acquire strength in a like proportion.
